    <section id="twin">
      <div class="section-head">
        
        <div class="eyebrow">Main Innovation</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Personalized NeuroDigital Twin</h2>
        <p class="section-lead">The NeuroDigital Twin is a personal baseline model. It learns what is normal for one user, then detects meaningful deviation by comparing live smartwatch and smartphone data against that user's own historical pattern.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="twin-map">
        <div class="twin-map-card">
          <h3>1. Personal Baseline</h3>
          <p>The system first learns the user's normal health and behavior patterns over time.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Normal HR and HRV range</li>
            <li>Sleep and recovery pattern</li>
            <li>Movement and tremor profile</li>
            <li>Typing and response behavior</li>
            <li>Genetic/family risk weight</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="twin-map-arrow">→</div>

        <div class="twin-map-card">
          <h3>2. Live Comparison</h3>
          <p>New incoming data is compared against the user's baseline, not only against public averages.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Smartwatch biosignals</li>
            <li>Phone behavioral biomarkers</li>
            <li>Sleep and stress changes</li>
            <li>Motion and fall signals</li>
            <li>Symptom check-ins when needed</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="twin-map-arrow">→</div>

        <div class="twin-map-card">
          <h3>3. Risk Prediction</h3>
          <p>When several deviations appear together, the AI raises a preventive risk score.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Cardiac strain index</li>
            <li>Neuro-motor risk index</li>
            <li>Autonomic stress index</li>
            <li>Smart alert level</li>
            <li>Doctor-shareable report</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="twin-summary">
        <strong>Simple explanation:</strong> the system creates a digital copy of the user's normal health rhythm. If the user's body or behavior starts moving away from that normal pattern, NeuroFusion AI treats the change as an early warning signal and recommends the appropriate next step.
      </div>
    </section>


    <section id="disease-targets" class="academic-section">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="section-number">07</span>
        <div class="eyebrow">Clinically Safe Risk Targets</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">What the System Can Reasonably Flag</h2>
        <p class="section-lead">These are prediction targets, not diagnoses. The system flags risk patterns based on measurable watch signals, phone behavioral biomarkers, personal baseline deviation, and genetic/family risk weighting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="clinical-targets">
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Motor Seizure / Epilepsy-Event Pattern</h3><p>Best suited for events with visible repeated limb movement, collapse, or autonomic changes.</p><ul><li>Watch: accelerometer, gyroscope, fall detection, HR, HRV, EDA/GSR.</li><li>Phone: missed interaction, emergency confirmation, caregiver alert.</li><li>Output: seizure-like motor event alert, not epilepsy diagnosis.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Parkinsonian Movement Pattern</h3><p>Targets gradual motor changes such as tremor, bradykinesia, and reduced movement regularity.</p><ul><li>Watch: resting tremor, reduced arm swing, slower movement, gait variability.</li><li>Phone: typing delay, touch instability, swipe irregularity.</li><li>Output: tremor/bradykinesia monitoring score.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>MS / Neuro-Fatigue Pattern</h3><p>Monitors fatigue, balance, mobility, and cognitive-motor fluctuation rather than diagnosing MS.</p><ul><li>Watch: activity decline, gait variability, falls, sleep recovery.</li><li>Phone: slower response, typing inconsistency, fatigue check-ins.</li><li>Output: mobility/fatigue deviation warning.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Stroke-Like Emergency Warning</h3><p>Used as an urgent safety flag when sudden behavior or movement disruption appears.</p><ul><li>Watch: fall, sudden inactivity, motion asymmetry, HR/SpO₂ context.</li><li>Phone: speech/typing disruption, failed response prompt, symptom check-in.</li><li>Output: emergency review recommendation.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Acute Cardiac Warning</h3><p>Combines rhythm, autonomic stress, oxygen, and user-reported symptoms for escalation.</p><ul><li>Watch: ECG/EKG, HR, HRV, SpO₂, EDA/GSR, temperature.</li><li>Phone: chest discomfort, shortness of breath, cold sweat, weakness check-ins.</li><li>Output: cardiac-event warning and care recommendation.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Heart Failure Strain Pattern</h3><p>Tracks long-term worsening trends rather than a single emergency reading.</p><ul><li>Watch: rising resting HR, HRV decline, sleep recovery, activity tolerance, SpO₂ trends.</li><li>Phone: fatigue logs, reduced daily function, cardiac family history.</li><li>Output: cardiac strain trend index.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Peripheral Artery / Circulation Pattern</h3><p>Works as a mobility and circulation-risk screen when walking capacity declines over time.</p><ul><li>Watch: reduced steps, walking endurance decline, HR recovery, skin temperature.</li><li>Phone: leg-pain check-ins and activity avoidance.</li><li>Output: peripheral circulation risk warning.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="target-card"><h3>Autonomic Nervous-System Imbalance</h3><p>Connects HRV, sleep, stress, temperature, and sweat-related signals into a regulation index.</p><ul><li>Watch: HR, HRV, EDA/GSR, sleep, temperature, stress load.</li><li>Phone: stress behavior, response slowing, wellness feedback loop.</li><li>Output: autonomic stress index.</li></ul></div>
      </div>
      <div class="research-note">Medical boundary: NeuroFusion AI is a preventive decision-support prototype. It predicts risk patterns and encourages review; it does not provide a final diagnosis or replace hospital-grade investigations.</div>
    </section>

